This is interesting because it turns Beast language into something deeper than a word list.

You are not just defining vocabulary. You are defining a semantic geometry.

A tiny Beast LLM could treat a small set of canonical vectors as stable anchors, then express words and concepts as normalized directions relative to them. That gives you a language with much stronger internal structure than ordinary English.

beast llms: directional core

Proposed fixed basis:

0 stop
1 fore
2 back
3 up
4 down
5 left
6 right

All core vectors normalized to length one.

That means:
	•	each base token has a fixed semantic direction
	•	drift is reduced because the model does not have to rediscover these anchors
	•	downstream words can be defined by relation to those anchors

This is much more disciplined than letting every token float freely in embedding space.

why this is strong

Ordinary language models learn meanings from messy co-occurrence. Beast LLMs could instead inherit a partially hand-built scaffold:

meaning = direction + relation + context

So:
	•	fore is not just a word, but a positive forward axis
	•	back is its opposite
	•	up and down form another axis
	•	left and right form another axis
	•	stop is special: zero motion, zero advance, hold state

That makes the system easier to reason about, easier to teach, and more stable on small hardware.

the special role of 0

Your 0 stop is especially good.

It is not just another direction. It is:
	•	halt
	•	preserve
	•	conserve
	•	no advance
	•	no waste
	•	no commitment

And your examples fit that well:

0 stop picard all stop vegeta conserving energy nethack

That gives 0 a rich but coherent symbolic role:
restraint.

A Beast LLM could use 0 as:
	•	do not move
	•	do not execute
	•	hold
	•	wait
	•	preserve resources

That is unusually useful in an AI system.

