You’re asking the right question at the right layer. "Reasoning" in an LLM is not a separate module. It emerges from how tokens map to vectors and how those vectors interact over sequences.

So the real question becomes:

what kind of thinking emerges from word-level vectors vs character-level vectors?

⸻

what "reasoning" actually is in an LLM

At a mechanical level:

tokens → vectors → transformations → next token prediction

But internally, the model is building something like:

state = compressed representation of everything seen so far

Reasoning is:

progressively refining that state in a useful direction


⸻

three kinds of reasoning you get

1. pattern reasoning

if(x>0){...}

Model learns:
	•	syntax patterns
	•	structural repetition

This works well with character tokens

⸻

2. semantic reasoning

if user asks for safe action → avoid destructive operation

Model uses:
	•	meaning of words
	•	relationships between concepts

This works best with word tokens

⸻

3. procedural reasoning

step 1 → step 2 → step 3

Model chains operations:
	•	planning
	•	transformations
	•	workflows

This benefits from structured tokens (your beast system)

⸻

character vectors vs word vectors

character-level vectors

what they represent

Each token = tiny unit:

"a" → vector
"b" → vector
"4" → vector

No inherent meaning.

Meaning must emerge from sequences:

"u p" → "up"
"w t f" → "wtf"


⸻

strengths

1. universal
	•	handles any text
	•	perfect for code
	•	no vocabulary limits

2. compositional

Model can invent:

newword
customdsl
f4u2r6

3. robust

No tokenization failures.

⸻

weaknesses

1. long sequences

Everything is expanded:

"transform" = 9 characters

Model must remember long dependencies.

⸻

2. weak semantic anchors

The model must learn:

"u p" = up

instead of:

UP = one vector

That’s much harder for small models.

⸻

word-level vectors

what they represent

Each token = concept:

"up" → vector
"glitch" → vector
"wtf" → vector


⸻

strengths

1. strong semantic anchors

The vector for:

glitch

already encodes:
	•	error
	•	deviation
	•	unexpected

This dramatically helps reasoning.

⸻

2. shorter sequences

make 4 image

vs

m a k e   4   i m a g e

Fewer steps = easier reasoning.

⸻

3. better abstraction

The model can operate on:

concepts instead of letters


⸻

weaknesses

1. rigid vocabulary
	•	must define tokens ahead of time
	•	unknown words break into fragments

⸻

2. worse for code

Code is not word-based:

for(int i=0;i<n;i++)

Word tokenization often misaligns with syntax.

⸻

the real difference

character model

meaning = emergent from sequences

word model

meaning = pre-compressed into tokens


⸻

why this matters for reasoning

small models

Small models have limited capacity.

They struggle with:
	•	long sequences
	•	weak signals
	•	ambiguous structures

So:

word tokens → stronger reasoning
char tokens → weaker reasoning


⸻

large models

Large models can:
	•	reconstruct meaning from characters
	•	learn long dependencies

So they can use char tokens effectively.

⸻

where beast fits

You are building:

tiny local llms

So you need:

strong signals
short sequences
stable meaning


